		<body>
			<div type="month" mhs:startingPage="967" 
				mhs:precedingFile="JQADiaries-v50-1847-01-p967.xml"
				mhs:followingFile="JQADiaries-v50-1847-03-p968.xml"
				mhs:volume="50">
				<bibl n="metadata"><date from="1847-02-08" to="1847-02-25"/></bibl>

				<!-- D/JQA/50 February 1847 P 967 to 969 -->
				
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v50-1847-02-08">
					<head>08 February 1847</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1847-02-08"/><editor
						role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Railroads</subject>
					<subject>Steam Power</subject></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p>I remained at <persRef ref="adams-charles2">my son’s</persRef> house in Boston, till Monday the <date>8<hi rend="superscript">th.</hi>
							of February 1847</date>—when with <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">my wife</persRef>, my son, and <persRef ref="fader-margaret">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Fader</persRef>,
					we went by the rail road from Boston to Springfield where we lodged at <unclear>. .
					.</unclear></p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v50-1847-02-09">
					<head>09 February 1847</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1847-02-09"/><editor
						role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<pb n="968" type="ms"/>
						<p>The next day <date>Tuesday 9 Feb<hi rend="superscript">y</hi> 1847.</date> <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine;adams-charles2;fader-margaret">we</persRef>
					went by the rail road from Springfield through Hartford to New-Haven, and by
					Steamboat from New-Haven to New-York, where we arrived about 9 O’Clock in the
					evening and took lodgings at the city Hotel—</p>
						
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v50-1847-02-10">
					<head>10 February 1847</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1847-02-10"/><editor
						role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
				<p><date>Wednesday 10. Feb<hi rend="superscript">y</hi> 1847.</date> Rain the whole day— Confined to the
					House— <persRef ref="johnson-alexander2">Alexander S. Johnson</persRef> <persRef ref="johnson-william4">William C. Johnson</persRef>, <persRef ref="hellen-walter2">Walter Hellen</persRef> called upon <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine;adams-charles2;fader-margaret">us</persRef> the
					two latter going to-morrow to Utica— Also <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hart</persRef>, <persRef ref="saltus-nicholas">Nicholas
						Saltus</persRef> and <persRef ref="brooks-sidney">Sidney Brooks</persRef> also called upon us—</p>
						
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v50-1847-02-11">
					<head>11 February 1847</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1847-02-11"/><editor
						role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Railroads</subject></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>Thursday 11. Feb<hi rend="superscript">y</hi> 1847.</date> <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine;adams-charles2;fader-margaret">We</persRef> came by the Railroad to
					Philadelphia, by the way of Camden and took lodgings at the Union hotel in
					Chesnut Street, no longer kept by <persRef ref="jones-john10">Jones</persRef>—</p>
						
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v50-1847-02-12">
					<head>12 February 1847</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1847-02-12"/><editor
						role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Railroads</subject>
					<subject>Adams Family Residences</subject></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>Friday 12. February 1847.</date> <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">my wife’s</persRef> birthday—she is 72 </p>
						<p><persRef ref="adams-charles2;fader-margaret">We</persRef> came by Railway to Baltimore where we dined at the United States Hotel, and
					then to Washington where we arrived at our house in F. Street at 8 O’Clock in
					the Evening.</p>
						
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v50-1847-02-13">
					<head>13 February 1847</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1847-02-13"/><editor
						role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
				<p><date>Saturday 13. Feb<hi rend="superscript">y</hi> 1847.</date> I took my Seat in the house of
					Representatives of the United States, and thenceforward attended the house daily
					till Wednesday the 3<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> of March 1847 the close of the Session
					and of the 29<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> Congress.</p>
				<p>Wednesday.</p>
						
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v50-1847-02-16">
					<head>16 February 1847</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1847-02-16"/><editor
						role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>Tuesday <unclear>16</unclear> Feb<hi rend="superscript">y</hi> 1847.</date> My Son <persRef ref="adams-charles2">Charles F Adams</persRef> left <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine;fader-margaret">us</persRef> and
					returned to Boston</p>
						
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v50-1847-02-25">
					<head>25 February 1847</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1847-02-25"/><editor
						role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
				<p>From the 25<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> of February to the 3<hi rend="superscript">d.</hi> of
					March, I sat several times in the Committee rooms, of the Committee room of the
					Committee room of the Committee of Post Offices and Post roads of the House of
					Representatives, to <persRef ref="powell-william">William H. Powell</persRef> a Portrait painter, at his request, but he
					did not finish the picture till after the close of the Session of Congress.</p>
						<pb n="969" type="ms"/>
						<p>And he was clothed with a vesture dipped in blood; and his name is called
							the Word of God. </p>
						<p>Revelation 19.13.</p>
						<p>26 And the foundations of the wall, of the city were
							garnished with all manner of precious stones. The first foundation was
							jasper, the second sapphire</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
